Design Claim Formula
A final claim should be compact enough to defend:
\[
\text{claim}
=
\text{condition}
+ \text{mechanism}
+ \text{evidence}
+ \text{action}
+ \text{limit}
\]
Example structure:
For this occupied condition, the dominant thermal burden is caused by this mechanism, shown by these artifacts, reduced by this design action, and limited by this uncertainty.

Week 10 Hint Level
::: {.hint-card minimal} Minimal hints.
Every guess must name:

mechanism;
intervention;
competing constraint;
evidence needed. :::

Sustained Climate Situations
Do not only ask for the hottest hour.
Look for situations that architecture has to endure:

hot nights that prevent recovery;
humid heat that weakens evaporative cooling;
low wind that makes air movement unreliable;
cloudy humid periods with poor drying;
heatwave duration rather than peak temperature;
future windows where present-day thresholds are crossed more often.


A3 can use a simple pair: baseline window plus one changed climate or stress snapshot. A4 can later ask whether the selected action still holds.

Week 8 Hint Level
::: {.hint-card thinner} Hints are now about uncertainty, not answers.
Guess:

typical week versus heatwave;
dry-hot versus humid-hot;
short stress window versus long window;
current EPW versus future-adjusted EPW;
indoor boundary versus outdoor exposure. :::

Moisture Also Has Memory
Humidity is not only an air-state variable. It can persist in materials, corners, storage zones, porous finishes, shaded surfaces, and maintenance routines.

A simple design reading:

moisture risk = source + cold surface + weak drying path + time


Architectural consequences:

a dehumidifier can dry the measured air while closets or wall corners remain damp;
cold surfaces can turn vapor into local condensation;
porous materials may buffer moisture briefly, then become a reservoir;
stagnant air can make drying slow even when the room average looks acceptable.


The goal is not to size every system to the maximum. The goal is to identify where moisture accumulates, where it dries, and what architectural path makes that possible.

A3 Outputs

Temporal Build-Up Audit:

one time-series or sequence strip;
one threshold line or target;
one degree-hour, exceedance, or accumulated exposure calculation;
explanation of build-up or lag mechanism;
one failure statement;
one candidate design action.

Week 6 Hint Level
::: {.hint-card thinner} Moderate hints.
Guess through time:

morning warm-up;
afternoon solar gain;
night cooling failure;
surface or moisture storage;
gusty versus reliable air movement;
threshold duration rather than peak. :::

Diagnostic Translation

Build a four-frame storyboard from the host case:

starting condition;
heat or moisture gain;
delayed or accumulated response;
candidate design action.



Humidity prompt:

What do you already know from living or working with humidity? What does a single dehumidifier change, what does it fail to change, and how does it transform the space?

Why Outdoors Is So Radiant


Outdoor thermal experience can be dominated by radiation because solar load, sky exposure, ground surface temperature, and shade quality change rapidly.
Air temperature may vary slowly. Radiant exposure can change when the body takes two steps.


Architectural objects:

canopy depth;
tree shade;
pavement material;
facade reflection;
courtyard sky view;
bench orientation.

Solar And Sky In The Urban Canyon
At ground level, radiant environment can vary sharply across a few meters:

sunlit pavement versus shaded pavement;
high sky view versus narrow canyon;
reflective facade versus absorptive facade;
hot ground longwave versus vegetated edge;
evening surfaces releasing stored heat after sun has moved.


Do not use air temperature alone to compare a shaded arcade, a sunlit crossing, and a narrow canyon. They may belong to the same weather file but not the same radiant field.

A2 Prompt

Find or construct two positions where air temperature alone does not explain the thermal condition.
Good cases:

window seat versus interior seat;
shaded bench versus sunlit bench;
glass facade perimeter versus deeper plan;
concrete courtyard versus vegetated edge;
roof terrace sun patch versus shaded threshold.



For each position, name the dominant radiant source or sink: direct sun, sky, hot surface, cool surface, reflected solar, or night-sky exposure.


Tool route for the first pass: A2 Radiant Box Tool. Use it to compare two body positions, export a heatmap and CSV, then state what the rectangular proxy cannot prove.

Week 4 Hint Level
::: {.hint-card thinner} Hints become narrower.
Guess through:

what surface occupies the body’s view;
whether the body faces or turns away from it;
whether shade changes shortwave radiation or only visual glare;
what surface temperature would have to be measured. :::

Heat Transfer Modes




Downloaded reference figure: Wikimedia Commons.



Architectural translations:

conduction: contact with seat, floor, slab, envelope;
convection: air speed, fan, downdraft, ventilation path;
radiation: warm glass, cold window, sun patch, hot pavement;
evaporation: humidity and sweat effectiveness.

The same modes appear in building physics, outdoor microclimate, and fire/tenability thinking.

Humidity, Evaporation, And Dehumidification
High humidity affects the body’s cooling pathway because evaporation becomes less effective.
For buildings, this becomes a design and operation question:

dehumidification can improve thermal tolerance without simply lowering Ta;
very humid interiors can support mold risk and material damage;
humid outdoor air can make ventilation costly or uncomfortable;
dry air can also become a health and comfort problem in other climates.


For your A1 case, name whether the likely comfort issue is primarily air temperature, humidity, air movement, radiation, or an interaction.

Heat Stress Is A Body Failure
Comfort asks whether a condition is acceptable. Heat stress asks whether the body can keep rejecting heat.

In hot-humid conditions, the dangerous direction is:

heat production + heat gain &gt; heat loss


Architectural warning signs:

high humidity weakens evaporation;
low air speed limits convective and evaporative relief;
high radiant load keeps adding heat even if Ta looks moderate;
long duration turns discomfort into accumulated physiological burden;
vulnerable occupants, activity, clothing, and access to control change the risk.


This is why Week 2 treats indices as claim systems. PMV, WBGT, UTCI, heat index, and adaptive comfort do not make the same promise.

Ladybug Route: What To Export
If students use Ladybug Tools later, ask them to document:

which comfort model or component they used;
the source of Ta, MRT, RH, and air speed;
metabolic rate and clothing assumptions;
whether the case is indoor, outdoor, mixed-mode, or naturally ventilated;
whether the output is point-in-time, annual hours, or a scenario comparison;
what the model does not see.


GH output only becomes course evidence when the input assumptions and model limits are visible.

Machine-Learning Analogy

Model output is reliable only inside a represented domain:

xcase ∈ Xtrained / validated / standardized


For architecture:

do not use PMV to answer every outdoor heat question;
do not use adaptive comfort for sealed mechanically conditioned assumptions without care;
do not use heat index to diagnose radiant asymmetry;
do not use UTCI as a facade-detail answer without spatial translation.


For your case, name the metric you would start with and one reason it might be the wrong metric.

Week 2 Hint Level

Still generous.
Guess through the body:

convection: air speed, fan, downdraft, still pocket;
radiation: hot/cold surface, sun patch, glass, sky view;
evaporation: humidity, sweat, dehumidification, clothing;
conduction: floor, seat, wall contact;
metabolism: activity and duration.

A3 Use
Use this kit when A3 needs a changed weather, window, or climate snapshot.
Minimum A3 transformation:

choose one city/scenario/year slice;
plot temperature, RH, GHI, or wind speed across the 14-day window;
set a threshold;
calculate failure hours or degree-hours;
state what design mechanism the weather sequence stresses: night recovery, shade, moisture, air movement, or service load.

A4 Use
For A4, this becomes a roll-forward check.
Possible claims:

a shading strategy remains useful under a hotter future window;
a passive ventilation claim weakens when wind is low during hot hours;
a humidity-sensitive material or dehumidification claim needs a different boundary;
a design action is robust in Guangzhou but not in Phoenix, or vice versa;
a conclusion is unsupported because the future-weather slice is not a microclimate model.

The important move is not scenario quantity. It is whether the student can say how the design claim changes when the weather boundary changes.

Grasshopper / Ladybug Bridge
Use the CSVs as a transparent handoff:

import hourly columns into Grasshopper for plotting or geometry-linked annotation;
use Ladybug/Honeybee weather workflows later if an EPW route is needed;
keep the selected city, scenario, year, threshold, and weather variables visible.

The architectural standard is the same as the rest of the course: the tool matters less than whether the boundary and claim are inspectable.

A2 Radiant Card Standard
A2 treats solar, sky, and surfaces as heat sources or sinks.
Use the A2 Radiant Box Tool when you need a transparent fallback model for a two-position comparison. Advanced workflows are welcome, but the required artifact is the comparison and claim, not the software route.
Each card should include:

two occupied positions with similar or comparable air-temperature context;
body orientation and major surfaces in view;
dominant radiant source or sink: direct sun, diffuse sky, reflected solar, hot surface, cool surface, or night sky;
approximate magnitude where possible: solar wattage order of magnitude, surface temperature, MRT difference, or operative-temperature contribution;
material-property note where relevant: reflectivity/albedo, absorptivity, emissivity, thermal capacity, or glazing transmittance;
one design implication: shade, surface temperature, material, sky view, body offset, facade depth, canopy, or controlled radiant surface;
one uncertainty statement.


A2 does not ask students to design homogeneous comfort. It asks them to identify how architecture can block, expose, cool, warm, store, or release radiant energy.

Roll-Forward Validation
The required final note is not a decade-by-decade retrofit thesis. Each student changes one stress assumption and asks whether the action still holds.
Examples:

hotter week instead of typical week;
3-day, 7-day, or 14-day stress window;
current versus future-adjusted weather;
dry-hot versus humid-hot period;
changed occupancy schedule;
changed glazing/window assumption.

The outcome should be labeled robust, weakened, censored, or unsupported. Multi-window reruns are distinction-level evidence when they improve architectural judgment, not because they add computation.

A3 Use
For A3, students can use the checked CSV directly.
Minimum A3 transformation:

choose a variable: air temperature, operative temperature, or another justified output;
declare a threshold;
count exceedance hours or degree-hours across the two-week window;
add the boundary table;
write a mechanism note explaining whether the pattern is driven by weather, service, storage, exposure, or model limits.

This is enough for a defensible temporal build-up audit. Rerunning EnergyPlus is optional.

A4 Use
For A4, this kit can become a seed rather than a final answer.
Possible extensions:

change the evaluation window;
compare the checked CSV with a student-generated Honeybee or EnergyPlus export;
hold the threshold fixed and test one design assumption;
use the plot as a model-limit example when explaining why a studio project needs a different boundary.

The final claim must stay bounded. A stock model can teach exposure-state reasoning; it cannot prove a student’s building performs.

Grasshopper / Honeybee Bridge
Students already working in Rhino/Grasshopper can treat the CSV as a handoff format:

import the CSV into Grasshopper for visualization;
reproduce the output route later through Honeybee/EnergyPlus;
keep the exported data, weather window, zone name, and service state visible.

The bridge rule is simple: a parametric workflow becomes evidence only when the assumptions and exported outputs remain inspectable.

Psychrometric Reading




Psychrometric chart source: Wikimedia Commons.



What this figure gives students:

dry-bulb temperature as only one axis;
relative humidity as a state relation, not decoration;
wet-bulb and moisture content as signals of evaporative stress;
a reason Hong Kong thermal claims cannot ignore humidity.


The point is not to memorize the chart in Week 1. The point is to see that air has more than one thermally relevant coordinate.

Stagnant Air Is A Thermal Condition
Same Ta, same RH, different experience:

air does not remove heat from the body effectively;
sweat evaporation may feel weaker in humid air;
moisture and odors can linger;
a corner, alcove, deep plan, or blocked path can become a local pocket;
the room average may look acceptable while the occupied position does not.


For A1, students can mark air movement qualitatively: still, weak, noticeable, fan-driven, diffuser-driven, cross-flow, or draft-prone.

Ventilation Is Not Cooling
Increasing outdoor air can improve perceived air quality and dilute pollutants.
It may also add:

sensible heat load when outdoor air is hot;
latent load when outdoor air is humid;
local draft near openings or diffusers;
uneven exposure if the airflow path bypasses occupied areas.


Ventilation, air movement, cooling, and comfort overlap, but they are not the same design claim.

Butterfly Route: What Must Be Declared
Before trusting an airflow image, document:

opening and inlet/outlet assumptions;
boundary conditions;
fan, heat source, or buoyancy assumptions;
mesh and solver setup;
where the body is located;
what the model does not include.


No boundary condition, no airflow claim. A beautiful CFD image is not evidence by itself.

Worked Example: Studio Perimeter


An architecture student says:

“The desk near the curtain wall is always uncomfortable.”

Possible readings:

higher Ta near the facade;
higher RH because air is stagnant;
solar gain through glass;
warm surface radiation;
no air movement;
draft from diffuser or leakage path;
expectation or task duration.



A1 only takes the first step.
This week we do not solve the whole condition. We map whether the air, humidity, and air-movement field supports the claim.

Week 1 Hint Level

Hints are generous this week.
Guess using these lenses:

facade edge, roof, floor, threshold, courtyard, shaded interior;
high/low Ta;
high/low RH;
stagnant air pocket;
sensor location that could mislead the claim.

Diagnostic Translation

The class is not judging whether the design is good or bad. The class is practicing thermal reading.
For every guess, name:

the suspected problem spot;
the mechanism;
the design feature that might help;
the competing constraint.

Interpolation Is A Claim

A field value between sensors is estimated:

Ta(x,y) ≈ f(Ta,1, Ta,2, …, Ta,n, x, y)


Common routes:

nearest sampled point;
inverse-distance weighting;
smoothed contour / heat map;
manual diagram from a measured gradient.


Do not present a smooth contour as measured fact. Say how it was made and where the samples are sparse.

Measuring Air Movement Is Harder Than Naming It
Air speed near a body can change quickly by position, height, posture, opening state, fan setting, and diffuser direction.
For A1-level evidence, acceptable descriptions include:

measured air speed, if an anemometer is available;
visible airflow cue, such as fan, diffuser, open window, door gap, curtain motion, smoke/string test if safe;
qualitative label: stagnant, weak, noticeable, intermittent, draft-prone;
position note: head, torso, ankle, seated height, standing height.


Do not average away airflow. A draft at ankle height and still air at face height are different occupied conditions.

Perceived Air Quality And Thermal Comfort Can Split
Increasing outdoor air can make a space feel fresher by diluting odors and pollutants.
But the same move can:

increase humidity load in Hong Kong;
increase cooling energy demand;
create local draft discomfort;
move pollutants or heat toward another occupied position;
improve perceived air quality while worsening thermal stress.


For your case, separate the claim into two lines: one about thermal condition and one about perceived air quality.

SMART-Style Radiant Sensing


The course can incorporate a SMART-style radiant sensing module when hardware is available.
The key architectural payoff is not the device itself. It is the ability to compare:

air temperature;
surface temperature;
directional radiant signal;
globe or MRT proxy;
occupied position.



Sensor sophistication does not remove uncertainty. Better sensors make uncertainty more visible and more specific.

A1 Submission Checklist

Your A1 must include:

a plan or section with 3-5 sampling points;
Ta and RH values or a clearly labeled curated sample data set;
time stamp and sensor height;
air-movement observation or measurement note;
one point map, gradient map, marked differential, or clearly labeled contour/heat map;
field notes;
one defensible claim;
one claim you cannot defend yet.

Week 3 Hint Level

Generous, but now tied to evidence quality.
Guess through these tensions:

representative point versus occupied point;
visible sensor versus integrated sensor;
calibration and maintenance;
privacy and trust;
architectural finish, cost, and operations.

Diagnostic Translation

For one class guess, translate the sensor placement into a design decision:

what it measures;
what it misses;
where it lives architecturally;
which competing requirement could make it fail.

Night Sky As Heat Sink
Radiant exchange can cool as well as heat.
At night, surfaces with sky view can lose longwave radiation to the sky. That cooling can support roofs, courtyards, and outdoor surfaces, but it depends on:

sky view factor;
cloud cover and humidity;
surface temperature and emissivity;
wind and convective coupling;
whether stored daytime heat is still being released.


Urban heat island is partly a nighttime problem: dense surfaces store heat, sky view is reduced, wind paths can be weak, and the city may not release heat fast enough after sunset.

A2 Card Structure

Your Radiant Exchange Card must include:

two occupied positions;
air temperature comparison;
surface/radiant/MRT proxy evidence;
body orientation diagram;
one approximate radiant source/sink note, using wattage, surface temperature, material property, or MRT difference where possible;
one heat-flux or exchange sketch;
one architectural implication;
one uncertainty statement.



If your project geometry is too complex for the browser box, the point is still transferable: define surfaces, assign temperatures, estimate view fractions, compute T_mrt, then explain the design consequence.

Week 5 Hint Level
::: {.hint-card thinner} Moderate hints.
Do not treat the body as a point. Guess:

face, back, legs, head, feet, hands;
seated, standing, waiting, moving;
one-sided glass, pavement, wall, sky, canopy, or radiant panel;
what orientation or furniture change would alter exposure. :::

Diagnostic Translation

Turn the host reveal into a radiant exchange card:

body segment or side exposed;
source or sink;
design lever;
competing constraint;
uncertainty.

Heat Balance Handle
EnergyPlus solves a detailed heat balance. For architectural interpretation, keep this simplified balance visible:
\[
C_z \frac{dT_z}{dt}
=
Q_{solar}
+ Q_{internal}
+ Q_{envelope}
+ Q_{HVAC}
- Q_{loss}
\]
Read it as a design question:

Which gains are driving the state?
Which losses are available?
Where is storage delaying the peak?
Which term can an architect change?

Operative Temperature Reminder
A simplified operative temperature is a weighted combination of air and radiant conditions:
\[
T_{op,t}
\approx
w T_{a,t}
+ (1-w)T_{mrt,t}
\]
The weighting depends on air speed and heat-transfer context. In A3, state the version or output variable you used, then keep the claim within that definition.

Week 7 Hint Level
::: {.hint-card thinner} Hints are moderate.
Guess through outputs:

Ta, T_mrt, T_op, RH;
key surface temperature;
solar gains;
service state or ideal loads;
ventilation/infiltration assumption;
whether local airflow would require a different model;
time window and timestep. :::

Found, Censored, Unresolved
Use three possible outcome labels:
\[
\text{found}
\Longleftrightarrow
\exists i \in \{0,\ldots,k\}
\text{ such that }
D_i \le D_{target}
\]
\[
\text{censored}
\Longleftrightarrow
\forall i \in \{0,\ldots,k\},
D_i &gt; D_{target}
\]
\[
\text{unresolved}
\Longleftrightarrow
\text{the evidence is insufficient to classify the ladder}
\]
